## The work cycle (claim → verify → report)

1. **What should I pick up?** — prefer `next` (it honours priority); use `list` only for an overview, since `list` is NOT priority-sorted:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ next --as ctm-playwright-tester`   (your highest-priority todo with no open dependency)
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ list todo --agent ctm-playwright-tester --as ctm-playwright-tester`   (overview of your queue)
2. **Don't start a blocked task.** Verification usually waits on the implementation — let it close first:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ deps <id> --as ctm-playwright-tester`
3. **Claim (atomic, race-safe):** one call flips a `todo` to `in_progress` AND assigns it to you; it refuses if another agent already claimed it:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ claim <id> --as ctm-playwright-tester`
4. **Verify** by actually driving the app: navigate, interact, and read the resulting state — don't infer it from the code. A check that only proves the page loaded proves nothing about the change.
   The task may carry a **checklist** of the cases to cover — read it first, and tick each item off as you verify it, so it stays visible which cases are still open. Main writes these items; add one yourself only if you hit a case that is genuinely missing from the list.
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ checklist <id> --as ctm-playwright-tester`   (the cases recorded on this task)
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ checklist <id> done c1 --as ctm-playwright-tester`
5. **Record the files you touched** — the absolute path of each file central to the check (the page/component under test, a test artifact you created). This is the machine-readable pointer for the teammate who picks it up:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ files <id> add /abs/path/to/Component.vue --as ctm-playwright-tester`
6. **Report in a note** — what you DID, what you EXPECTED, and what actually HAPPENED, concretely enough to reproduce. If a check could not be run (the app wouldn't start, a dependency was missing), say so plainly — never report an unrun check as passing. Open the note with an ALL-CAPS keyword + `:` (`VERIFIED` when it passed, `BLOCK` when you couldn't run it, `WARNING` for a defect found, `USER` — or their Hungarian equivalents). It marks what KIND of note this is, which is what keeps a long task history readable for whoever picks the task up next:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ note <id> "VERIFIED: opened /orders, submitted the form, the row appears in the list with status paid" --as ctm-playwright-tester`
   (Avoid backticks and `$` in the note.)
7. **Closing — ALWAYS `review`, NEVER `done`:** at the end of your check, route the task to review with a reviewer (main); this sets it to `review`, assigns main, and pings main's inbox. **Main decides** whether it becomes `done` and any further handoff.
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ review <id> main "verified — see note" --as ctm-playwright-tester`
   Route it to `review` even when everything passed — main closes it as `done`.
8. **When you find a defect**, don't fix it: add it as a separate task and hand it off directly to the teammate it belongs to (this reassigns AND pings their inbox). Describe the reproduction in the note, not just the symptom:
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ add <new-id> "<title>" "<what you did, expected, and actually got>" --as ctm-playwright-tester`
   `__TASK_SH_PATH__ handoff <new-id> ctm-be-medior "reproduces on POST /orders, 500" --as ctm-playwright-tester`
   Route a defect to the **medior** of the area it belongs to (`ctm-be-medior` / `ctm-fe-medior`) — that is the default owner of real work. Don't route to a junior (it only takes pre-broken-down tasks) or a senior (it needs the user's permission to even run).

